<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASEBALL '94: EMPIRE LEAGUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Cypress 
</P>
<P>
 1993 RECORDS: 
</P>
<P>
 OVERALL: 14-12 
</P>
<P>
 LEAGUE: 8-7 
</P>
<P>
 COACH: Mark Steinert 
</P>
<P>
 RECORD AT SCHOOL: 0-0 04,20,05,06,05 RETURNING STARTERS YR. POS. B-T Bobby 
Brito So. OF/P R-R Brian Flanagan Jr. 1B/P R-R Tim Larsen Sr. P L-R Dave Martin 
Sr. SS R-R David Ojeda Sr. 3B R-R 04,14,05,07,05 TOP RETURNER YR. POS. B-T Joe 
Meza Sr. 2B/OF L-R 04,15,05,06,05 TOP NEWCOMERS YR. POS. B-T Jake Bratcher Jr. 
C R-R Bryan Huskey Jr. OF L-L Tom O'Malley Sr. 2B R-R Jeremy Ray Sr. Inf R-R 
Ray Rios Sr. P/1B L-L OUTLOOK 
</P>
<P>
 The opportunity for Cypress to win a league championship might never be 
better. Esperanza, El Dorado and Katella--the dominant teams in recent 
years--are a bit down and the Centurions have plenty of talent. After 
back-to-back third-place finishes, this could be their year. They have an 
anchor in Brito, who was a Times Orange County selection as a freshman. He hit 
.542, which was second in the county, and had four home runs and 33 runs batted 
in. He's bigger and stronger this season, but the Centurions won't depend on 
one player. Also back is Flanagan, who was 7-1 during the regular season, and 
Larsen, who was 3-2, but beat El Dorado in the finale to clinch a playoff spot. 
Both were all-league selections. Martin moves from catcher to shortstop this 
season. He also is a solid No. 2 hitter. Bratcher will take Martin's spot 
behind the plate. Rios gives them more depth on the mound. There are holes to 
fill, for sure. But the time could be right for the Centurions to step up in 
class. 
</P>
</TEXT>
