<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; 3 INDICTED 
IN ALLEGED FRAUD SCHEME AIMED AT LATINOS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Three Los Angeles men who allegedly bilked 4,000 Latino investors from 
Southern California out of $10 million were indicted on federal mail fraud 
charges, a prosecutor said Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
 Anthony Fadel, 30, Epigmenio Sandoval, 37, and Jose Castellanos, 35, were 
indicted on 18 counts each of mail fraud.Fadel also was charged with three 
counts of money laundering.  
</P>
<P>
 Assistant U.S. Atty. Ellyn Lindsay said the men, through the Fadel Group 
Investment Corp., solicited investors via Spanish-language radio and television 
stations, and through newspaper ads.  
</P>
<P>
 The defendants, Lindsay alleged, persuaded the investors to place their money 
with the Fadel group by promising rates of return of up to 24%. In exchange, 
the prosecutor alleged, Fadel, Sandoval and Castellanos promised to provide 
gems and property as a security. Instead, he said, the three men spent the 
money on themselves, giving out only gems and land deeds that were virtually 
worthless. 
</P>
<P>
 If convicted, Fadel faces up to 150 years behind bars and $6 million in fines. 
Sandoval and Castellanos face up to 90 years incarceration and $4.5 million in 
fines apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
