<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST PUMMELED AGAIN BY SNOW, SLEET AND RAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Another major storm system slammed the Eastern Seaboard on Wednesday, dumping 
snow, sleet and rain from Maine to Florida. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're pretty sick of this," said Rhonda Lynch, a legal secretary in 
Martinsburg, W. Va."We're hoping that if March is coming in like a lion, it'll 
go out like a lamb." 
</P>
<P>
 As much as two feet of snow was possible in the hills of western Maryland and 
south-central Pennsylvania, the National Weather Service reported. 
</P>
<P>
 The big storm extended along most of the Eastern Seaboard and Appalachians, 
with snow edging into New England at the same time Florida had thunderstorms 
and at least one tornado. Flooding in the Sunshine State brought out snakes and 
floating clusters of fire ants. 
</P>
<P>
 As the storm slowly chugged up the coast, Maryland was pelted with rain and 
snow, and New Jersey got a nasty mixture of several inches of snow topped with 
sleet and rain. Massachusetts' heaviest snowfall was not expected until this 
morning's rush hour. Up to a foot of snow was expected in the western end of 
the state, with 20-foot seas along the coast. 
</P>
<P>
 Virginia Gov. George F. Allen declared a state of emergency after the state 
was hit with snow in the north and freezing rain in the south. There were more 
than 170,000 power outages statewide, and numerous roads in the southern part 
of the state were blocked by falling trees. 
</P>
<P>
 Ten inches of snow fell Wednesday on Virginia's central Blue Ridge near 
Charlottesville and Winchester. Up to five inches of snow in northern 
Virginia's Washington suburbs snarled traffic on Interstates 95 and 66. 
</P>
<P>
 Schools were closed in parts of western and northern Virginia, including 
Caroline County, where students have missed about two weeks of class this 
winter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
