<TEXT>
<P>
 SEC Chief Faults Inequities in Regulation: Banks that sell mutual funds are 
not subject to the same regulations as securities firms, and that's bad for 
investors and perhaps for the overall economy, Securities and Exchange 
Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt Jr. told the House Energy and Commerce 
Committee's investigations panel, which is reviewing the planned merger of 
mutual fund Dreyfus Corp. and Mellon Bank Corp. With the merger, Mellon and its 
affiliates would be the largest mutual fund investment adviser, managing $76.8 
billion in mutual fund assets. But Levitt noted that federal law exempts banks 
from the rules that cover brokers and investment advisers, including SEC 
inspections. 
