<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEYWIDE FOCUS: VOLUNTEERISM PROJECT GETS A HELPING HAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By REBECCA BRYANT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In setting their 1994 agenda, directors of the fledgling Los Angeles 
Volunteerism Project had pinpointed disaster response as a priority. 
</P>
<P>
 But when the Northridge earthquake jolted Los Angeles awake Jan. 17, the 
luxury of planning disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
 "So when this happened it was, 'Uh oh. The horse was out of the barn before we 
built the barn,' " said Pat Paolilli, director of the project. 
</P>
<P>
 The nonprofit Volunteerism Project, which started in late fall and handled its 
quake relief efforts from the Panorama City office of the Volunteer Center of 
the San Fernando Valley, was designed to coordinate six privately funded 
volunteer centers in Los Angeles County. The aim is to increase volunteerism 
throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
 The project was modeled after a San Francisco program that increased community 
volunteering by 45% in three years. The San Francisco project worked out a 
disaster plan for that area in response to the Loma Prieta quake, but the Los 
Angeles group had not gotten that far. 
</P>
<P>
 "So we just started working," Paolilli said. "Our colleagues in San Francisco 
faxed us some plans." 
</P>
<P>
 The project brings together the volunteer centers of the San Fernando Valley, 
Greater Pomona Valley, Los Angeles , La Mirada, San Gabriel Valley and South 
Bay-Harbor-Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 In the days after the quake, volunteers from all six centers filed into the 
San Fernando Valley center in Panorama City. 
</P>
<P>
 By Thursday, 10 telephone lines had been installed and calls from people 
wanting to volunteer and agencies needing manpower starting pouring in. 
</P>
<P>
 "By Friday noon it was clear to us we were under-phoned. So we ordered 20 more 
lines," Paolilli said. 
</P>
<P>
 In the 36 days it took calls, the hot line matched 3,600 volunteers with about 
600 agencies that asked for help, said Suzanne Lewis, the center's spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
 Now that the immediate crisis is over, operators are monitoring the phones 
until Friday, taking messages and suggesting volunteering opportunities. 
REBECCA BRYANT 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
