<HEADLINE>
<P>
MERCURY CLIMBS INTO THE LOW 80S; WEATHER: SLIGHTLY COOLER BUT STILL-SUNNY 
CONDITIONS WILL LINGER. RECORD-BREAKING 87-DEGREE READING IS LOGGED IN DOWNTOWN 
LOS ANGELES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANNA CEKOLA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Unusually warm temperatures, including a record-setting mark in downtown Los 
Angeles, sent many to the beaches Wednesday and made it seem like summer had 
arrived early. 
</P>
<P>
 "Usually, January through March is the rainy season in Southern California," 
said Curtis Brack, a meteorologist for WeatherData, which provides forecasts 
for The Times."But of the larger storms that usually come through, very few 
have developed." 
</P>
<P>
 While temperatures may cool a bit in the next few days, forecasts call for 
more sunny and dry weather, Brack said. 
</P>
<P>
 Locally, temperatures reached 78 degrees in Santa Ana, 83 in Fullerton and 82 
in Lake Forest. The same-day record for Orange County is 87 degrees, set 16 
years ago in Santa Ana, according to WeatherData. The normal temperature for 
this time of year is about 69 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
 In downtown Los Angeles, the mercury hit 87 degrees, breaking the 86-degrees 
record set on the same date in 1910, the National Weather Service reported. 
</P>
<P>
 Nowhere was evidence of the heat greater than at local beaches, where bigger 
than usual crowds were reported, including 16,000 people in Newport Beach and 
about 15,000 at Huntington Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 Said Newport Beach Marine Safety Lt. John Blauer: "It was enough to make us 
think summer is almost here." 
</P>
</TEXT>
