<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUPLE KILLED OUTSIDE APARTMENT IDENTIFIED; VIOLENCE: MAN WAS FATALLY SHOT 
WHILE SITTING IN A PARKED CAR. WOMAN IN THE DRIVER'S SEAT WAS SLAIN AFTER SHE 
TRIPPED WHILE FLEEING. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Authorities Wednesday identified the bodies of a man and woman killed outside 
a Lancaster apartment complex. 
</P>
<P>
 A Los Angeles County coroner's spokesman said a fingerprint check determined 
that the woman was Latonya Walker, 23, of Adelanto, a town near Victorville in 
San Bernardino County. 
</P>
<P>
 The man, also identified through fingerprint records, was identified as Ronald 
Greene, 22, of Upland, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Deputy Rich Erickson said. 
</P>
<P>
 The victims were sitting in a parked car just after midnight Tuesday when a 
man armed with a .44-magnum pistol approached the rear passenger window and 
shot Greene in the head, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
 Walker, who was in the driver's seat, ran from the car but tripped, deputies 
said. She begged the gunman not to shoot, telling him that she had three 
children, witnesses reported. But the man fired three times, striking her in 
the head, hand and upper torso, deputies said. 
</P>
<P>
 The gunman then walked a short distance away, placed the weapon on the ground 
and continued walking, deputies said. Investigators later recovered the gun. 
They also discovered that Greene was carrying several thousand dollars when he 
was killed. 
</P>
<P>
 "Detectives believe the case may be narcotics-related," Sheriff's Deputy 
Benita Hinojos said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 The slaying occurred outside an apartment complex in the 43400 block of 32nd 
Street West. 
</P>
<P>
 "In years past, we've had a lot of problems there with narcotics trafficking 
and gangs," said Sgt. Bob Denham of the Antelope Valley sheriff's station. "But 
for the last several years, it's been very quiet over there." 
</P>
<P>
 No further progress on the case was reported Wednesday. The Los Angeles-based 
homicide detectives assigned to the case were out of town, attending an 
investigators' convention, the sheriff's homicide bureau said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
