<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: PASADENA; SCHOOL OFFICIAL TO LEAVE FOR NEW POST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A school district administrator demoted last year for concealing the removal 
of a special-education department computer will become superintendent of an 
Imperial County school district this month. 
</P>
<P>
 Michael Klentschy, 49, administrator of elementary instruction, told the 
Pasadena school board last week that his goal had always been to become a 
superintendent for a school district.He will assume the top educator position 
in the El Centro School District, next to the Mexian border, on March 14, 
almost a year after he was demoted from associate superintendent. 
</P>
<P>
 The demotion came after the school district discovered he had helped conceal 
the removal of the computer by then district security chief Charles Parcell to 
his department. 
</P>
<P>
 According to Pasadena police, Klentschy authorized moving the computer to the 
security office. However, after special-education workers discovered the 
computer missing, Klentschy reportedly supported the theory it had been stolen. 
As a result, Klentschy's annually salary was cut from $86,900 to just over 
$77,000. He also forfeited $15,000 in vacation pay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
